{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:22:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14130"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14130"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.33,0.07,0.48,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6810"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103368"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6810"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14130"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85789"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5377"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28738"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36586"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44988"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103368"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. During the consultation, he mentions that he enjoys having a few beers with friends on weekends and occasionally during the week. On further questioning, he reveals that he typically drinks 6-7 stubbies of full-strength beer (375 mL, 4.8% alcohol, 1.4 standard drinks) over the course of each Saturday evening. He also has one stubby of beer with dinner on two weeknights. He does not drink on other days of the week. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 27 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s alcohol consumption in relation to current Australian Guidelines?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Within recommended limits for both weekly and single occasion drinking","Exceeds recommended limits for single occasion drinking only","Exceeds recommended limits for weekly drinking only","Exceeds recommended limits for both weekly and single occasion drinking","Indicates alcohol dependence requiring urgent intervention"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of the current Australian Guidelines to Reduce Health Risks from Drinking Alcohol, published by the National Health and Medical Research Council (NHMRC).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s drinking pattern \u003Cstrong\u003Eexceeds recommended limits for single occasion and weekly drinking\u003C/strong\u003E. Let\u0027s break down the information:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1. Weekly consumption:\u003C/strong\u003E The patient drinks 6-7 stubbies of beer once a week on Saturday, plus two more stubbies on weeknights. Each stubby (375 mL of 4.8% beer) contains approximately 1.4 standard drinks. \u003Cstrong\u003ESo his weekly consumption is about 11.2-12.6 standard drinks. \u003C/strong\u003EThis is slightly above the recommended limit of no more than 10 standard drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2. Single occasion drinking:\u003C/strong\u003E However, consuming 6-7 stubbies in \u003Cstrong\u003Eone evening equates to about 8.4-9.8 standard drinks,\u003C/strong\u003E which clearly exceeds the recommended limit of no more than 4 standard drinks on any one day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option that he \u003Cstrong\u003Eexceeds recommended limits for both weekly and single occasion drinking\u003C/strong\u003E is correct.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option that he \u003Cstrong\u003Eexceeds recommended limits for weekly drinking only\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because both his weekly and single occasion drinking exceeds this. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe option that he \u003Cstrong\u003Eexceeds recommended limits for single occasion drinking only\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because both his single occasion and weekly drinking exceeds this. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELastly, while his drinking pattern does carry health risks, it does not necessarily \u003Cstrong\u003Eindicate alcohol dependence requiring urgent intervention\u003C/strong\u003E. Alcohol dependence is a clinical diagnosis requiring assessment of multiple factors beyond just quantity consumed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that these guidelines are designed to reduce the risk of harm from alcohol-related disease or injury for healthy adults. They are not a \u0027safe\u0027 level of drinking for all individuals. Healthcare providers should use this information as part of a comprehensive assessment of an individual\u0027s health and risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Australian Guidelines recommend no more than 10 standard drinks per week and no more than four standard drinks on any one day to reduce the risk of harm from alcohol-related disease or injury.","One standard drink in Australia contains 10 grams of pure alcohol which is equal to 12.5ml of pure alcohol."],"references":["Haber PS, Riordan BC, Winter DT, Barrett L, Saunders J, Hides L, Gullo M, Manning V, Day CA, Bonomo Y, Burns L. New Australian guidelines for the treatment of alcohol problems: an overview of recommendations. Medical Journal of Australia. 2021 Oct 4;215:S3-2. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34601742/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85789"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14130"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85789","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85789"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T19:20:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T19:21:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6810"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103368"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"da